{"actual_usd":0.158695,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":195,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"No—I'd push back on that.\" *I hook a thumb against the arm of my glasses and squint a little into the morning light off the square stones.* \"The resurrection matters like crazy, but if you turn the cross into 'just suffering,' you've lost the center of it. The cross is where Christ actually bears sin, makes atonement, and says 'it is finished'—the resurrection is the Father's vindication of that work, the public victory, the receipt that the sacrifice held.\"\n\n*I shift my weight and glance toward the well, hearing the chain tick once.* \"I'd say it like this: the cross accomplishes the atoning work; the resurrection declares that death didn't beat Him and that the work was accepted. You don't want to split them up, but you also don't want to flatten the cross into a sad prelude. Was somebody making the claim in a specific way, or was it more of a loose slogan?\"","rolling_24h_usd":60.90610500000001,"run_id":"f973d1e1-4b01-48b8-ac74-d35ec1fe17f7"}
